## Diagnosis

The two-axis grammar (color channel + weight channel) is architecturally correct but both axes are miscalibrated. The resting state is rendering at 2px — identical to the engaged state — meaning the weight channel has no range to work across. There is zero visual distance between resting and focused, so the engagement signal is lost.

**Anti-pattern: AP-072** — Collapsed state axis (two states share the same value on a discriminating dimension, eliminating the signal the dimension was introduced to carry).

---

## Root Cause

The resting border is being set with the same utility class or token value as the engaged ring. Most likely one of two causes:

1. The `border` utility defaulted to `border-2` somewhere in the component or a global reset overrode `border` to `2px`.
2. The focus ring is being painted *in addition to* a 2px border, rather than *replacing* the weight on the border — so the base border was bumped to 2 at some earlier fix and never walked back.

---

## Fix

### 1. Token layer — establish the weight axis explicitly

```css
/* packages/elan/tokens/src/scale/border.css  */

@layer elan.tokens {
  :root {
    /* Weight axis */
    --border-weight-rest:    1px;   /* hairline — resting */
    --border-weight-engaged: 2px;   /* bold    — focused / active */

    /* Color axis (unchanged from previous fix) */
    --border-color-rest:     var(--color-neutral-300);
    --border-color-engaged:  var(--color-accent-500);
  }
}
```

---

### 2. Input primitive — apply both axes correctly

```tsx
// packages/elan/primitives/src/Input/Input.tsx

const inputVariants = cva(
  [
    // Layout & typography (unchanged)
    "w-full rounded-md px-3 py-2 text-sm bg-surface-base text-content-primary",
    "transition-[border-color,box-shadow] duration-150 ease-out",
    "outline-none",

    // ── Weight axis ──────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Resting: hairline border (1px)
    "border border-[length:var(--border-weight-rest)]",

    // ── Color axis ───────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Resting: neutral stroke
    "border-[color:var(--border-color-rest)]",

    // ── Engaged state: paint-only ring, NO border-width change ───
    // Box-shadow carries the 2px weight; border stays at 1px so
    // layout is not disturbed (paint-only = zero layout impact).
    "focus-visible:border-[color:var(--border-color-engaged)]",
    "focus-visible:shadow-[0_0_0_1px_var(--border-color-engaged)]",
    //                                 ↑
    // The shadow offset = 1px sits flush against the 1px border,
    // giving the visual impression of a 2px engaged stroke without
    // actually changing border-width.
  ],
);
```

> **Why `box-shadow` instead of `border-width: 2px` on focus?**
> Changing `border-width` at focus shifts surrounding layout geometry — content jumps. A `box-shadow` ring is paint-only; it occupies no layout space. This is the canonical pattern (used by Radix, Headless UI, and the ARIA authoring practices guide).

---

### 3. Remove any global reset overrides

Check and correct these two common culprits:

```css
/* apps/web/src/styles/globals.css  — BEFORE (wrong) */
*, *::before, *::after {
  border-width: 2px;   /* ← this is the likely offender */
}

/* ── AFTER (correct) ── */
*, *::before, *::after {
  border-width: 0;     /* Tailwind Preflight default */
}
```

```css
/* packages/elan/tokens/src/components/input.css — remove if present */

/* DELETE any rule like: */
.input {
  border-width: 2px;   /* ← was set during a previous ring fix, never reverted */
}
```

---

### 4. Verify visually with a state matrix test

```tsx
// packages/elan/primitives/src/Input/Input.stories.tsx

export const WeightAxisMatrix: Story = {
  render: () => (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-4 p-8">
      <label className="text-xs text-content-secondary">Resting — should read as hairline (1px)</label>
      <Input placeholder="Resting" />

      <label className="text-xs text-content-secondary">Focused — should read as bold (2px visual weight)</label>
      <Input placeholder="Focused" autoFocus />

      <label className="text-xs text-content-secondary">Error — color axis only, weight stays at resting</label>
      <Input placeholder="Error" aria-invalid="true" />
    </div>
  ),
};
```

---

## Principle

**The weight axis must have range.** If resting and engaged share the same `border-width`, the axis carries no information — it is a one-value scale, which is not a scale. Resting = hairline (1px) establishes the floor. Engaged = visually bold (2px) establishes the ceiling. The gap between them *is* the signal. Use a paint-only `box-shadow` ring at focus to deliver that weight change without disturbing layout geometry.
